{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528127"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.21,0.05,0.09,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6961"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84877"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-day history of painless swelling of both of his legs. He has lost 8 kg of body weight over the last two months for no apparent reason. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer a day. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. He has bilateral pitting oedema up to his knees. The rest of the examination is normal. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal cell carcinoma","Abdominal aortic aneurysm","Psoas abscess","Retroperitoneal haematoma","Lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large retroperitoneal mass abutting the aorta and compressing the inferior vena cava (IVC) (Image). This compression explains the bilateral leg swelling. Given the patient\u0027s presentation with B symptoms (fever and unintentional weight loss) and the imaging findings, \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a retroperitoneal mass, but it typically arises from the kidney and would be unlikely to cause IVC compression. While it can cause systemic symptoms, the combination of B symptoms and bilateral leg swelling is more suggestive of lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a dilated aorta on CT, which is not seen in this case. Additionally, it would not typically cause bilateral leg swelling or systemic symptoms like fever and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E could present with fever and a retroperitoneal mass, but it would typically be unilateral and associated with more localized pain. The absence of pain and the presence of bilateral leg swelling make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretroperitoneal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically have a more acute onset and be associated with trauma, anticoagulation, or a bleeding disorder. The gradual weight loss and lack of pain make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphoma, particularly non-Hodgkin lymphoma, can present with enlarged retroperitoneal lymph nodes that coalesce into a mass. This mass can compress surrounding structures, including the IVC, leading to bilateral leg swelling. The presence of B symptoms (fever and weight loss) further supports this diagnosis. Definitive diagnosis would require biopsy of the mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of B symptoms, bilateral leg swelling, and a large retroperitoneal mass on CT imaging is most consistent with lymphoma. Further workup would include laboratory tests (complete blood count, lactate dehydrogenase, liver and kidney function tests) and ultimately a biopsy for definitive diagnosis and classification of the lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lymphoma often presents with B symptoms including fever, night sweats, and unintentional weight loss.","Compression of the inferior vena cava by a retroperitoneal mass can cause bilateral leg swelling.","CT imaging is crucial in diagnosing retroperitoneal masses and lymphadenopathy."],"references":["Armitage JO, Gascoyne RD, Lunning MA, et al. Non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Lancet 2017; 390:298-310."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84877"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21061"},{"type":"media","id":"21062"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21910"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21061"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9AFH08lR4aFkrJJpGQVva7oLwS5BQU.jpg","thumbUrl":"htt